WEBVTT

00:04.655 --> 00:06.457
Okay, this is just a sound check. Bob, say 
something. Hello, my name is Bob.

00:11.402 --> 00:12.964
How many people check this door here? Probably 
like 100. I don't know why they can't have it open.

00:16.247 --> 00:25.237
Okay, this is Ron Shorn, and I'm interviewing Bob 
Havlin at the American Astronomical Society

00:16.247 --> 00:25.237
Berkeley meeting on June 6, 1993. So, Bob, for the 
record, what's your full name? Robert James

00:29.201 --> 00:30.903
Havlin. How do you spell that? H-A-V-L-E-N. Where 
were you born? Utica, New York. And when? 1943. A

00:38.228 --> 00:38.488
date? Oh, yes, September 16. How did you get 
interested in astronomy in the first place? I

00:46.319 --> 00:50.965
think it was a Boy Scout project or a science fair 
project when I was in the sixth or seventh grade. I

00:51.385 --> 00:53.709
had to draw some maps of the night sky and find 
north. That started my desire to look through

00:55.231 --> 01:02.320
telescopes and to buy a telescope and eventually 
made my own telescope and Gradually became more

01:02.992 --> 01:05.976
and more in contact with the astronomical 
community. I was good at school. Where did you go to

01:08.479 --> 01:09.640
undergrad school? Went to the University of 
Rochester. And when did you graduate from there?

01:12.764 --> 01:13.925
1965. And what was your major? Astrophysics. Did 
you start out in astrophysics? I started out in

01:18.871 --> 01:20.233
astrophysics. Why? Why did I start in 
astrophysics? Because with my middle school and

01:24.057 --> 01:30.585
high school experience in making my own telescope 
and reading about astronomy, I decided that was an

01:31.105 --> 01:33.788
area that I wanted to go into. As a matter of fact, I 
only applied as an undergraduate to Cornell and to

01:33.808 --> 01:44.538
the University of Rochester in New York State 
because those were the only schools that had

01:33.808 --> 01:44.538
undergraduate degrees in astronomy. Where did 
you go to grad school and why? I went to the

01:49.163 --> 01:58.011
University of Arizona because I realized that I 
needed to be at a clear sight where I could get into

01:49.163 --> 01:58.011
astronomy. It had a good national reputation. It 
was growing. I applied to the University of

02:01.328 --> 02:03.672
Michigan and to Harvard. I got accepted at 
Michigan, didn't get accepted at Harvard, and

02:04.232 --> 02:12.465
then Arizona and NASA traineeship and so on. It was 
the best decision of my then young life because the

02:12.505 --> 02:23.622
University of Arizona, of course, is right across 
the street from Kitt Peak National Observatory.

02:25.144 --> 02:26.927
So what did you do at Arizona? At Arizona, I... I got 
interested in x-ray astronomy and optical

02:31.467 --> 02:40.575
astronomy and no radio astronomy really. And 
gradually did a thesis under Bengt Westerlund

02:41.256 --> 02:53.287
using photographic data and photoelectric data 
on Cepheids and OB associations and the

02:41.256 --> 02:53.287
relationship of them. And when did you get out? Why 
did you pick that? Why did I pick that? Was it the

02:57.871 --> 02:59.072
person or the field? It was the... Person, 
primarily. I think it was the ease with which I was

03:02.525 --> 03:13.916
able to work with Dr. Westerlund and his vast 
experience in the field of observational optical

03:02.525 --> 03:13.916
astronomy. Of course, I was exposed to almost 
everything there was to be exposed to back in the

03:14.757 --> 03:27.310
late 1960s because of our interaction with Kitt 
Peak National Observatory. And there were

03:27.330 --> 03:30.313
theoreticians around. You know, I did fairly well 
at most of my courses, but I found

03:30.783 --> 03:47.185
after thinking about what I really wanted to do for 
three or four months, I decided that I wanted to go

03:30.783 --> 03:47.185
into studying Cepheids and OB associations with 
Beck. He was an interesting guy. He had lots of

03:49.488 --> 03:59.622
unreduced observational data to work with and was 
inspirational in helping me decide what further

03:49.488 --> 03:59.622
observations were to be made and so on. I think 
that's Sort of a typical interaction. It wasn't a

04:04.138 --> 04:09.848
question of money, as it is these days, because I 
was supported by a NASA traineeship. Was that your

04:10.409 --> 04:14.916
first contact with an ASA? Yes, basically it was.

04:20.826 --> 04:22.869
When did you finish your degree? I finished in late 
1969. When you were a grad student at Stewart, did

04:25.728 --> 04:35.421
any of the infighting, well, or let's put it this 
way, Kuiper and Bart Bock were perhaps not the

04:25.728 --> 04:35.421
world's greatest friends? You know, I didn't 
really get too much feel from that. I mean, Bock

04:40.748 --> 04:46.656
came in 1967, after I'd been there a couple of 
years. He was always telling stories about Kuiper

04:47.328 --> 04:58.225
and Bach, and I don't know, there was another guy, 
another Dutchman that came over to the U.S. about

04:47.328 --> 04:58.225
the same time as those two, and I can't remember. I 
think it was a guy

04:58.245 --> 05:07.359
in Peter Zandekamp, was it? No, but it's in Ray 
White's obituary about Bach, so we can look at it.

05:10.825 --> 05:11.866
Yeah, yeah, it's kind of neat. Did... Did people at 
Steward or Kitt Peak look down on planetary work as

05:15.593 --> 05:21.882
far as you know? Did the grad students say, oh, if I 
can't get in with somebody that does stellar work,

05:22.263 --> 05:27.931
I'll have to do planetary work? Was any of that kind 
of stuff still left when you were there? I don't

05:33.279 --> 05:33.860
think so. Now that I think of it,

05:33.900 --> 05:44.335
being a graduate student at Steward was an 
interesting experience because you had lunar and

05:33.900 --> 05:44.335
planetary lab right across the street. And the 
people that did planetary science, like Tom

05:44.939 --> 06:04.040
Garrels, like Pat Romer, I can't think of a few more 
names that were associated with the lunar and

05:44.939 --> 06:04.040
planetary. They were there, yeah, exactly. And I 
never got the feeling that this was...

06:12.884 --> 06:14.426
a secondary science. There was Bill Hartman, for 
example. He was there. I mean, it was interesting

06:16.769 --> 06:17.970
stuff. It just so happened that you really do have a 
difference of opinion as to whether you want to go

06:17.990 --> 06:26.920
into planetary science. I mean, planetary 
science is almost like geology. It's close to

06:28.682 --> 06:29.423
home. And at least that was my feeling. I didn't 
want to get into planetary science. And I knew

06:33.548 --> 06:36.051
other graduate students that really didn't want 
to get into planetary science. They were more

06:36.071 --> 06:37.913
interested in stars and galaxies. And that just is 
sort of a natural, because there were graduate

06:38.551 --> 06:43.037
students. As a matter of fact, Ben Zellner, who's 
now, I guess he does asteroid work with Garrels.

06:54.932 --> 06:57.175
There was Kofin. There was a few other graduate 
students. Planetary science was a real

07:00.740 --> 07:03.544
challenge. It just wasn't something that I wanted 
to get into. Where'd you go after you got your

07:06.207 --> 07:08.490
degree? uh in january of 1970 we packed our bags put 
our car on a boat got on an airplane and went to chile

07:09.213 --> 07:38.798
i uh i became a staff member at the european 
southern observatory and primarily because

07:09.213 --> 07:38.798
westerland my thesis advisor six months earlier 
had become the director there and he said bob why

07:09.213 --> 07:38.798
don't you come down for a year so i said fine a year 
i'll go anywhere ended up being settled What did

07:39.655 --> 07:41.617
you work on there in general? In general, I was a 
staff astronomer, of course, and I had to assist in

07:42.498 --> 07:55.933
all the equipment for all the visiting 
astronomers in terms of Kude spectrographs,

07:42.498 --> 07:55.933
Castorine spectrographs, single channel 
photometers, and so on. And I continued my

07:56.754 --> 08:05.764
interest in OB associations and started 
surveying some of the southern Milky Way in terms

07:56.754 --> 08:05.764
of accumulating data that would allow us to then 
determine whether or not the young blue stars we

08:06.352 --> 08:16.347
were detecting were actually members of 
associations or whether they were just in the

08:06.352 --> 08:16.347
field. And when did you leave there and why? I left 
there in May of 1977 and we'd been in Chile seven

08:20.313 --> 08:34.435
years and our daughters were then one and four 
years so we decided to come back to the States and We

08:34.938 --> 08:38.083
didn't want our kids growing up Chilean, 
basically. And the position I got in the US was as a

08:39.244 --> 08:45.994
lecturer at the University of Virginia in 
Charlottesville. And I found it very difficult to

08:47.116 --> 08:54.587
look for a position from outside the US to get back 
into the US. And so I was very grateful to be able to

08:54.647 --> 09:01.637
get some kind of temporary position from which I 
could use as a base to look for a more permanent

08:54.647 --> 09:01.637
position. And that fell into place, 
unfortunately, upon the death of Nelson

09:02.174 --> 09:10.983
Lindbergh. This is D. Nelson Lindbergh. D. Nelson 
Lindbergh, exactly. And so what was this

09:14.147 --> 09:16.329
permanent placement? Well, the position I got was 
University of Virginia as lecturer. And I was

09:20.473 --> 09:24.738
actually on the staff there for two years. And at 
the end of the second year. Which would be 1979. In

09:28.955 --> 09:43.669
the middle 90s, after academic year 78, 79, I then 
took up a position at the National Radio Astronomy

09:28.955 --> 09:43.669
Observatory, more of an administrative position 
as assistant to the director with Mark Roberts. At

09:44.670 --> 09:54.440
that point, it was better not to have to move the 
family than to go to Washington, D.C. or someplace

09:44.670 --> 09:54.440
like that. Why did they pick you? I was a warm body. 
No, Mort Roberts and I got along very well. I had

10:01.267 --> 10:08.296
worked earlier as a summer student at NRAO in 1964 
in Greenbank with Mort. And I was interested in an

10:09.117 --> 10:14.444
administrative position because I had been 
interviewed. Actually, I had been offered a job at

10:14.584 --> 10:18.929
the National Science Foundation by Bill Howard. 
And so I was trying to decide, did I want to leave

10:19.750 --> 10:25.017
Charlottesville and move to Washington or what? 
And Mort had just taken a position as director at

10:25.037 --> 10:29.202
NRAO about six months earlier. And he realized 
that he needed help. So for me, it was a new

10:32.518 --> 10:35.422
challenge I was happy to move into. How long did you 
stay there? Oh, I was with the NRAO, actually,

10:38.447 --> 10:42.814
until just the beginning of this year. I was in 
Charlottesville until mid-1988. So that's 11

10:46.880 --> 10:52.489
years in Charlottesville and an additional four 
years in Socorro. At the VLA. At the VLA, right.

10:57.273 --> 11:07.530
When you first went into the National Radio 
Astronomy Observatory, did you notice any

10:57.273 --> 11:07.530
difference between optical and radio 
astronomers? As a matter of fact, I did. I've

11:10.074 --> 11:13.600
always noticed a difference between optical and 
radio astronomers. You want to know what that

11:14.542 --> 11:15.683
difference is? Yes, you mean going back to grad 
school days? Yeah, basically. I mean, in grad

11:19.748 --> 11:23.973
school, I have to admit that I never really came 
across that many radio astronomers. Oh, there was

11:24.034 --> 11:30.461
Frank Lowe, and there was the odd, I mean... Rare. 
The rare radio astronomer that would come

11:30.642 --> 11:33.926
through. We did have one radio astronomer on the 
staff, one official, quote-unquote, radio

11:34.406 --> 11:43.317
astronomer on the staff at the University of 
Arizona, and that was Andrei Pahulchik. And he

11:44.005 --> 11:57.217
taught the course in radio astronomy, and I found 
radio astronomy to be much, much greater, much

11:44.005 --> 11:57.217
more intensity in real physics. That is, radio 
astronomers seem much more solidly based and

11:57.918 --> 12:10.269
solidly ground, if you will, in

11:57.918 --> 12:10.269
techniques and a theory of physics. The 
frustration, of course, with the radio

12:12.001 --> 12:16.447
astronomers, I found, of course, was that they 
didn't have any good angular resolution. They had

12:16.507 --> 12:19.492
instrumentation that they had to be extremely 
careful with. It seemed to me that radio

12:19.552 --> 12:29.166
astronomers knew a lot more about the inner 
workings of the computer than optical. I can't

12:29.246 --> 12:30.367
take that back. Optical astronomers generally 
knew a lot about their spectrographs and their

12:30.447 --> 12:37.838
polarimeters and photometers because they had to 
make it work. Radio astronomers... however, had

12:39.473 --> 12:49.128
found the nice technique of relying upon a really 
high-quality staff of radio engineers and

12:39.473 --> 12:49.128
computer scientists. And so the actual 
astronomers really didn't know that much about

12:49.168 --> 12:59.884
the black boxes they were using, but the people 
that did made everything work exceedingly well.

13:00.204 --> 13:05.312
And at the NRIO, I noticed that most of the radio 
astronomers that I dealt with hardly ever would,

13:05.731 --> 13:09.617
they sort of looked down upon optical astronomy. 
They didn't care really what a spectral type was or

13:09.657 --> 13:15.186
what constellation or anything like that. They 
were really retooled physicists or retooled ham

13:15.206 --> 13:22.176
radio operators more than anything. Whereas 
optical astronomers tended to be types that got

13:22.717 --> 13:34.135
excited about astronomy from hands-on observing 
experiences when they were either in high school

13:22.717 --> 13:34.135
or college. And there was a rare optical 
astronomer who got into optical astronomy

13:34.672 --> 13:46.067
because they were good in physics and they were 
good in theory and then got pushed into optical

13:34.672 --> 13:46.067
astronomy. But in general, I thought the problems 
that radio astronomers were asking and were able

13:46.107 --> 14:00.105
to answer were a lot more in-depth in physics and 
global problems than optical astronomers were

13:46.107 --> 14:00.105
asking. Maybe that was naive, but that's my 
impression. Okay, so this year, early this year, I

14:02.667 --> 14:10.360
guess, you left Socorro, and where did you go? I 
left the... Actually, I left the NRAO, and I left

14:10.400 --> 14:20.356
Socorro both at the same time, and I'm now 
executive director of the Astronomical Society

14:10.400 --> 14:20.356
of the Pacific. And for me, it's an ideal position 
because... You know, I've sort of been a hybrid

14:24.622 --> 14:27.765
between optical and radio astronomy. I've never 
really put my solid foot down and said, this is my

14:27.785 --> 14:35.393
area, and I am pigeonholed forever. I just really 
get excited about all problems in astronomy, and

14:35.433 --> 14:45.384
I've always been involved with public outreach 
and public information since coming back to the

14:35.433 --> 14:45.384
NRAO. When I was in Chile, of course, I was working 
hand-in-hand in glove with all the visiting

14:50.069 --> 14:52.071
astronomers. So I got to see a broad perspective of 
the type of problems that everybody that came to

14:52.091 --> 14:57.717
the observatory was working on. And then when I 
came back to the U.S., I was involved with radio

14:58.418 --> 15:02.262
astronomy. So then I got a perspective of what it 
is, what it means to be a millimeter-wave

15:02.282 --> 15:13.174
astronomer or a centimeter-wave astronomer, or 
even a long-wave astronomer, and what the

15:02.282 --> 15:13.174
problems of resolution are. and different 
wavelength approaches to different problems.

15:17.467 --> 15:27.398
And so I found myself with quite a large global 
perspective that I guess I'm really now able to

15:17.467 --> 15:27.398
take advantage of in my dealings with the 
astronomical community. Why did you make this

15:27.759 --> 15:28.920
last jump? Was it because the opportunity was 
there? Basically, it was the opportunity was

15:31.343 --> 15:33.225
there. Andy Fracknoy had been the executive 
director of the Astronomical Society of the

15:33.265 --> 15:42.216
Pacific for the last 14 years or so. I saw the 
advertisement in one of the, I think it was the

15:42.922 --> 15:55.514
AAS's job newsletter, and said, I read the 
description, you know, it must be this, it must be

15:42.922 --> 15:55.514
that, and experience of this, experience of that. 
I said, you know, this is a job I can do. I can do all

15:58.437 --> 16:00.399
that stuff. I almost replied to that myself, and 
that would have been some competition, except

16:00.759 --> 16:09.068
that this NASA contract was already looking good. 
I see, I see. We already had word that we got it, you

16:09.888 --> 16:12.591
know, so... And also I have to add that it was more or 
less an opportunity for me to be my own boss, as it

16:14.022 --> 16:20.871
were. It's kind of hard to work year after year 
after year, sometimes having ideas that your boss

16:21.051 --> 16:29.583
doesn't necessarily share, enthusiasm, 
support, and so on. And now in this position, I can

16:30.243 --> 16:33.848
sort of make it or break it. I can pave new ground if I 
really get enough energy up to do it. So you've done

16:39.676 --> 16:42.780
optical, you've done radio, and now you have... I 
have to do everything. I have to do everything.

16:45.242 --> 16:49.387
Which is one of the reasons I want to interview, 
because I'm going to start asking you some

16:45.242 --> 16:49.387
questions now today.

16:53.792 --> 17:07.089
How important do you think NASA money was to 
helping astronomy in general and planetary

16:53.792 --> 17:07.089
astronomy in particular take

16:53.792 --> 17:07.089
off? Well, I don't know where to begin to answer 
that question, of course, For NASA, to answer

17:12.730 --> 17:35.329
about the importance of NASA money to astronomy in 
general, I'd say that the educational

17:12.730 --> 17:35.329
opportunities that NASA money afforded to people 
like me, even though I never ended up in planetary

17:12.730 --> 17:35.329
astronomy, the research that I did never really 
affected any of the NASA missions. It was really

17:35.748 --> 17:47.744
invaluable at the time because I was able to go 
through graduate study without worrying about

17:35.748 --> 17:47.744
teaching assistants or outside jobs or what have 
you. Of course, I've seen the NASA money and the

17:48.905 --> 18:01.261
support that it provided to the, I guess it was the 
Mount Lemmon 61-inch telescope and all the

17:48.905 --> 18:01.261
research work that got done there. NASA money... 
You know, the telescope on Mauna Kea, there's a

18:05.718 --> 18:12.985
NASA telescope there, infrared facility. 
There's two, there's the 88 inch and the IRT.

18:16.649 --> 18:18.151
That's right, that's right. And I think in 
hindsight I would say NASA probably could have put

18:18.171 --> 18:33.166
more money in ground support to some of their 
missions than they did. I mean, it's always Ground

18:35.705 --> 18:45.939
support has always been looked upon by the people 
in national centers as only funded by the National

18:35.705 --> 18:45.939
Science Foundation. The question has always been 
raised, for example, how much impact will the

18:47.422 --> 19:00.480
space telescope or any of the other NASA-funded 
orbiting telescopes have on ground-based

19:00.967 --> 19:05.092
facilities? And should NSF worry about having to 
fund more ground support and so on? I mean, you get

19:13.983 --> 19:17.828
the idea that the...

19:20.931 --> 19:30.383
I think we've always worried about is

19:20.931 --> 19:30.383
the demand for ground support going to overwhelm 
the telescopes on the ground once we get all these

19:31.257 --> 19:36.486
observations from space. And I think the answer 
has been sort of halfway between the real terror

19:36.867 --> 19:46.824
and the optimism. I mean,

19:46.884 --> 19:56.320
my opinion has always been that, hey, there's only 
24 hours in a day and there's a limited number of

19:46.884 --> 19:56.320
astronomers. And if they're off getting X-ray 
data, they don't have time to be getting radio data

19:56.705 --> 20:03.371
from the ground or optical data from the ground. 
There's no doubt that every single space

20:04.152 --> 20:17.484
observatory that has returned data has changed 
the character of the proposals that have been

20:04.152 --> 20:17.484
submitted to the ground-based support . I mean, 
for example, back in 1983, when IRS data started

20:18.365 --> 20:25.632
coming down, the 12-meter telescope probably had 
like 40, 50 percent of its proposals for the next

20:26.506 --> 20:40.325
three or four years were always mentioning IRS 
data this and IRS data this and we're following up

20:26.506 --> 20:40.325
this from IRS and that from IRS. Basically, the 
number of proposals did not overall to the

20:41.106 --> 20:45.733
telescope didn't increase. The character of the 
proposals changed because researchers were

20:45.973 --> 20:51.501
getting data from infrared and now they wanted to 
compare it to multi-wavelength. That's exactly

20:53.107 --> 20:57.674
paralleled in planetary ground-based observing 
every time a probe goes by. Exactly, exactly,

20:57.914 --> 20:59.877
exactly. One question before I forget here, 
because I skipped around a little bit. 30 years

21:04.784 --> 21:08.430
ago, if we'd be in an AAS meeting, there'd just be 
one AAS meeting. Everybody would be in here. Now,

21:10.333 --> 21:13.978
you don't see many planetary papers. You don't see 
many solar papers. We've got all these divisions,

21:15.990 --> 21:26.140
high energy, astrophysics, solar astronomy, 
planetary astronomy, historical astronomy. And

21:26.281 --> 21:29.264
some of them have their own specialized journals 
now. In addition, in the old days, it was APJ, AJ,

21:29.284 --> 21:38.093
and PASB, Publications of the Astronomical 
Society of the Pacific. Do you think these

21:38.512 --> 21:48.042
subdivisions of the AS have been good or bad, or 
just inevitable?

21:51.085 --> 22:07.202
I think you put the nail on the head when you said 
inevitable, because the general expansion of the

21:51.085 --> 22:07.202
field makes it, I mean, even the American Physical 
Society just cannot have a general meeting where

21:51.085 --> 22:07.202
everybody exchanges information in a worthwhile 
manner. on a broad diversity of topics. I mean, as

22:11.350 --> 22:37.476
much as I, in the astronomical side of the Pacific, 
feel that the public needs to be exposed to a broad

22:11.350 --> 22:37.476
range of topics in a general sense, you know, solar 
astronomy, planetary astronomy,

22:11.350 --> 22:37.476
extra-galactic astronomy, all the wavelength 
and so on, and it's good to meld them all into one

22:11.350 --> 22:37.476
sort of uniform picture, at the detailed 
professional level, where you're talking

22:11.350 --> 22:37.476
researcher to researcher, The meetings, and 
especially the division meetings, extremely

22:37.777 --> 22:46.486
important that they're talking on the same 
topics. You would totally dilute the effort if you

22:46.506 --> 22:53.133
were to mix extragalactic types with the division 
meetings. The data transmission rate would be

22:53.153 --> 22:55.776
very low. On the other hand, it's also very 
important, a very important part of these

22:55.996 --> 23:03.344
meetings is to have the overall survey talk. 
You'll find a very high percentage of the members

23:08.135 --> 23:28.316
of the AAS are younger graduate students or people 
that are in academic positions where they're

23:08.135 --> 23:28.316
teaching on all subjects and for them to have a 
broad perspective of what's going on in planetary

23:08.135 --> 23:28.316
science or X-ray astronomy or high energy 
astrophysics or you name it. In this meeting it

23:28.336 --> 23:37.365
seems to be extreme ultraviolet astronomy and in 
other meetings it's been IRAS and sometimes it's

23:28.336 --> 23:37.365
the ultraviolet astro program I mean, it's 
essential to have these overviews sort of cycle

23:37.598 --> 23:55.395
around all the disciplines in astronomy so that 
your younger folks or your people that are

23:37.598 --> 23:55.395
teaching general courses and so on have a good 
perspective of the big picture. You can't chop it

23:55.936 --> 24:01.562
up so little that planetary sciences only go to 
planetary science meetings. It's not fair. Do you

24:04.745 --> 24:07.167
think planetary astronomy is part of astronomy? 
Do I think it's part of astronomy? That's a good

24:11.161 --> 24:12.043
question. I think it is part of astronomy, but I'm 
asking myself, why do I think it's part of

24:13.325 --> 24:19.155
astronomy? We use telescopes. That's right. 
Planetary scientists use telescopes. Some of

24:26.308 --> 24:30.555
them use space probes, however, which are not 
