31:11.100 --> 31:15.866
question of optical versus radio, I think you have 
to be very, very careful.

31:18.569 --> 31:32.447
Because radio astronomers have always been 
really totally dependent very soon after the

31:18.569 --> 31:32.447
beginning of radio astronomy. Radio astronomy 
actually began in the 1930s and really wasn't

31:32.933 --> 31:44.910
going full force until the 1950s after the war, and 
very soon thereafter was the creation of national

31:32.933 --> 31:44.910
observatories. So radio astronomers have 
always, not always, but for the most part, have

31:44.930 --> 31:53.522
been using national facilities. You just know 
they cannot spend the money at a local university

31:53.682 --> 32:00.612
to build an instrument big enough, so it's been 
national facilities. And it's a much smaller

32:00.963 --> 32:10.173
population of scientists, let's say probably 
between 10% and 20% of the number of optical

32:00.963 --> 32:10.173
astronomers. And so the people to do the fighting 
are fewer. The efficiency of getting telescope

32:16.460 --> 32:28.152
time for the members of the community because of 
the existence of large national centers like

32:16.460 --> 32:28.152
Arecibo and NRAO and so on, and some major 
university facilities like Owens Valley and so

32:28.790 --> 32:34.218
on. It's much more successful for radio 
astronomers to get telescope time. Optical

32:40.487 --> 32:45.254
astronomers, on the other hand, they come from a 
different community at the outset.

32:45.754 --> 32:55.428
Historically, they grew up in large private 
telescopes like Lick and Mount Palomar and so on.

32:55.448 --> 32:57.531
And so they were in-house type astronomers. And 
only over the course of the last three decades, so

32:58.000 --> 33:11.914
to speak, since the NSF was founded, have you 
